SIMPLE: impulsion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impulsion
<hw>Im*pul"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>impulsio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>impulsion</ets>. See
<er>Impel</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of impelling or driving onward, or the state
of being impelled; the sudden or momentary agency of a body in motion on
another body; also, the impelling force, or impulse.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>impulsion</xex> of the air.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Influence acting unexpectedly or temporarily on the
mind; sudden motive or influence; impulse.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>impulsion</xex> of conscience.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Clarendon.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧Divine <xex>impulsion</xex> prompting.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impulsive</ent>⟦br⟧
